If I had to guess the narrative, Waymo and GM Cruise probably were rushing to fulfill (internal?) testing deadlines by end of 2018 and crammed a lot of testing into Nov 2018. Unless there's similar situation this year - and Oct data so far does not indicate it - we should expect the big Nov/Dec falloff that happened in previous years. Caveats: we don't know if any company has (internal) deadlines to do more testing this year before EOY; pre-2018 years had less testing overall and Nov/Dec falloff might not be comparable.

Through September 10, 2019: (a) Waymo = 12, (b) Cruise = 40 and (c) All Other = 11. That said, Q3 ends Sep 30, so we have only seen about 75-80% of Q3, so we must adjust for days in Q. For Q4, we observe that Waymo had an anomalous Q2, so we throw it out of the data when making an extrapolation. We then must make assumptions for Q4 based on what we have seen for Waymo, GM and other, which gets us to our result. I have no idea how crowd is getting such weird numbers.

Revising my estimation method slightly to try and incorporate some suggestions from @cafebedouin & @nigster. I'm keeping my primary estimation (assumed mileage increase rate * assumed decreasing accident rate) but am now incorporating both a lower extremized total which uses the assumed end of year 2019 accident rate (16.88 APMm*) & and an upper extremized total which uses the end of year 2018 accident rate (29.67 APMm) and then am bringing them back together in a weighted average (1:2:1). This yields the following range of estimates... Lower Extreme: 85.8 accidents Primary Estimate: 87.5 accidents Upper Extreme: 106.1 accidents

The 2018 report listed about 73 crashes, almost all by Waymo and GM, who had together about 275 vehicles. and drove about 1 million and 1/2 million miles respectively, at a rate of about 00.0001 crashes per mile, or 0.1 crash per thousand miles, which is quite lower than the national average of learning drivers of 1.5 per thousand miles and about the same as a competent driver. Rethinking the right hand tail of my subjective view of the probability distribution function. On the one hand, driverless car testing has lost some momentum. On the other hand, as I stated on Dec. 28, the marketing hype for driverless cars continues as if none of the bad news of 2018 had happened. On the third hand, and this is why I'm scaling back the right hand tail of the probability distribution function, I hadn't factored in the possibility of the Great Recession, or even a typical recession, barging in sometime in 2019. Whenever recessions happen, the majority of venture capitalists rush to close their pocketbooks. I've worked for venture entities for several decades now, seen it all.

Most recent data I could find through 20 minutes with Google show a rate of .03 accidents/car on the road for regular cars (would be more useful to see accidents/mile logged but I couldn't find that easily). Autonomous vehicles (AVs) on the other hand seem to have had a ~.17 accident/car rate in 2018...probably down to them being on the road for far more miles/car given they're being tested all the time. This is a much harder question than it appears. Partially because the question is not well defined and partially because it is not a static situation. The question does not state what Level of autonomy we are judging. There are 5 levels from something like enhanced cruise-control to fully autonomous. There is also the vagueness in the question regarding "testing" autonomous vehicles versus consumer autonomous vehicles. For example, there are no Level 5 consumer vehicles on the road, but there are several companies testing Level 5 vehicles on the roads in CA.

A naive estimation would look at: Miles driven / miles driven per accident reported and how those values are expected to develop in 2019. Miles driven: https://www.therobotreport.com/self-driving-cars-disengagements/ Waymo (Alphabet's self-driving venture) had by far the most miles driven in 2016 and 2017, -44% less miles driven in 2017 compared to 2016, though. It looks like many miles driven will shift to Phoenix, where they plan to roll out their first commercial autonomous ride service. (https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2018/03/02/waymo-is-millions-of-miles-ahead-in-robot-car-tests-does-it-need-a-billion-more/#627ab2311ef4) Nevertheless, other companies will continue to test and probably ramp up their mileage, although they might be discouraged by what seems like Waymo being way ahead of the curve here. But since the companies playing catch up are both large (GM, Nissan) and potentially a few smaller startups, I think it would be reasonable to assume that miles driven in CA will be higher. For this forecast I would go with 1 million miles driven in CA as the lower bound, 3 million miles driven as the upper bound. This could also go significantly higher if commercial operations involving autonomous cars start popping up, so will have to keep an eye out for that. One thing that might need clarification in this question: Will only accidents reported in vehicle testing be included or would the count include accidents by commercially and regularly operated fleets? Miles driven per accident reported: The PLoS One paper (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5607180/) cites 40-54k miles driven per accident for Google's vehicles, see Table 2. Other companies do much worse with 3k-20k miles driven per accident. A pessimistic outlook for this parameter would be: - no progress from Google/Waymo, so they would remain at ~50k miles driven per accident. - the rest of the pack manages to catch up to the best from the paper, so the rest has an accident every 20k miles driven. An optimistic outlook for this parameter would be: - Google/Waymo manages to beat the average of conventional cars in the US (500k miles/accident). Considering they want to launch a commercial service, they pretty much have to be measured by that standard in order to gain their customers' trust. - The rest catches up halfway, so 250k miles/accident. There is a fair chance they might get better even faster, as once a pioneer has led the way it's easier for competitors to follow, poach people who have know how from a project that succeeded, etc. This technology might be starting to take off exponentially, which is always hard to wrap one's head around in a forecast.
